<div id="c4">
<p><em>the databases are always a small part of a larger picture, supplemented with interviews, documents, and even undercover investigation</em></p>

<p>This doesn&#8217;t refute the need for transparency websites.</p>

<p>I&#8217;m not sure if we should ever have expected the general population to visit watchdog websites to help them vote&#8230; I think the point was to allow investigative journalists to &#8220;outsource&#8221; the menial parts of data collection/analysis. That way, those who already have the persistence to do investigative journalism get more of it done, and we lower the barriers to entry to the profession for hobbyists.</p>

